         <h2 class="top-headline landing-headline">Protect your email address from spam and other malicious threats</h2>
      <section class="landing-sensitive-info">
        <h3 class="sb-callout relay-sub">What is email masking?</h3>
        <p class="sb-callout-body">Most apps require an email address. When you give out your real email address, it can be picked up by hackers who use it to take over your online accounts, or trackers who sell or trade it online to make money. When you use email masking, you give apps a random, anonymous email address to keep your real email address private.</p>
        <h3 class="sb-callout relay-sub">How does it work?</h3>
        <p class="sb-callout-body">Email masking services generate unique and anonymous email addresses for your accounts, and then forward emails to your real email address. Most services also let you block or delete an address, so you’ll never receive emails from it again - even if the address was somehow added to spam lists.</p>
        <h3 class="sb-callout relay-sub">Our recommendations</h3>
        <!--
        <ul class="-list">
            <li class="article-list-item">Don’t give out your email address if you don’t have to. No-one can steal data that doesn’t exist.</li>
            <li class="article-list-item">Some email providers have ways to create additional addresses. For example, <a href="https://gmail.googleblog.com/2008/03/2-hidden-ways-to-get-more-from-your.html" rel="" target="_blank">Gmail offers “plus addressing”</a> and <a href="https://help.yahoo.com/kb/mail/SLN3523.html" rel="" target="_blank">Yahoo Mail offers disposable email addresses</a>.</li>
            <li class="article-list-item">Services like <a href="https://burnermail.io/" rel="" target="_blank">Burner Mail</a> have browser extensions to use or generate anonymous addresses for any website that asks for your email.</li>
        </ul>
        -->
      </section>

